Credit Score Classification¶

Final Project for DTSA 5509 (Introduction to Machine Learning)
by Yasushi Yamanaka (yasushi.yamanaka@colorado.edu)

1. Introduction¶

1.1 Background¶

Credit scores are crucial for determining if someone can get a loan or credit. Traditionally, experts used statistical models to calculate these scores. But now, machine learning methods are changing the game. Machine learning algorithms can analyze a lot of data and find patterns that humans might miss. This project focuses on using machine learning to classify credit scores. By training algorithms on past credit data, we can teach them to identify important patterns and make accurate predictions about someone's creditworthiness. We'll use different classification algorithms for comparison. The goal is to create a reliable credit scoring model that lenders can use to assess risk and make better decisions. This will help them reduce financial risks while offering loans to deserving individuals.

1.2 Objectives¶

This project is about building machine learning models on credit-related bank data. The data is originated from Kaggle and the problem belongs to *multiclass classification problem of supervised learning*. Different classification algorithms will be tested and compared in this project, including Logistic Regression, Decision Tree Classification, Random Forest Classification, and Gradient Boosting Classification. Comparison will be based on classification evaluation metrics and time efficiency. Optimal model with good balance of accuracy and efficiency is recommended at the of the study based on testing results. In addition, data handling and analysis techniques required for model training will be demostrated.

1.3 Data Source¶

  • ROHAN PARIS. (2022). Credit score classification. [Data Set] https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/parisrohan/credit-score-classification
  • Origin and gathering method of this dataset are not revealed in the website
  • Problem Statement from the website: You are working as a data scientist in a global finance company. Over the years, the company has collected basic bank details and gathered a lot of credit-related information. The management wants to build an intelligent system to segregate the people into credit score brackets to reduce the manual efforts.

3.2 Converting Columns to Correct Datatypes and Formats¶

  • Columns to convert: Month, Age, Annual_Income, Num_of_Loan, Num_of_Delayed_Payment, Changed_Credit_Limit, Outstanding_Debt, Amount_invested_monthly, Monthly_Balance
  • For those values converted unsuccessfully (due to invalid format), we set them as NA

df["Month"] = pd.to_datetime(df["Month"], format='%B').dt.month
df["Age"] = pd.to_numeric(df["Age"],errors="coerce")
df["Annual_Income"] = pd.to_numeric(df["Annual_Income"],errors="coerce")
df["Num_of_Loan"] = pd.to_numeric(df["Num_of_Loan"], errors="coerce")
df["Num_of_Delayed_Payment"] = pd.to_numeric(df["Num_of_Delayed_Payment"], errors="coerce")
df["Changed_Credit_Limit"] = pd.to_numeric(df["Changed_Credit_Limit"], errors="coerce")
df["Outstanding_Debt"] = pd.to_numeric(df["Outstanding_Debt"], errors="coerce")
df["Amount_invested_monthly"] = pd.to_numeric(df["Amount_invested_monthly"], errors="coerce")
df["Monthly_Balance"] = pd.to_numeric(df["Monthly_Balance"], errors="coerce")
  • Occupation, Credit_Mix, and Payment_Behaviour are categorical but have some random values, we set those random values to NA
  • Credit_History_Age is in the format of XX Years and X Months, so we parse it and turn it into numeric format
  • Type_fo_Loan is categorical but can have multiple values, so we standardize the format preparing for later transformation
In [7]:
df["Occupation"][df["Occupation"] == "_______"] = pd.NA
df["Credit_Mix"][df["Credit_Mix"] == "_"] = pd.NA
df["Payment_Behaviour"][df["Payment_Behaviour"] == "!@9#%8"] = pd.NA
df["Credit_History_Age"] = df["Credit_History_Age"].apply(lambda x: float(x.split(" ")[0])*12+float(x.split(" ")[3]) if pd.notnull(x) else x)
df["Type_of_Loan"] = df["Type_of_Loan"].str.lower().apply(lambda x: x.replace(", and ", ",").replace(", ", ",") if pd.notnull(x) else x)

  • Age, Num_Bank_Accounts, Num_Credit_Card, Interest_Rate, Num_of_Loan, Num_of_Delayed_Payment, and Num_Credit_Inquiries have obvious outliers
  • We apply 1.5*IQR rule (Interquartile Range) to find outliers in data and set them to NA
  • Num_Bank_Accounts, Num_Credit_Card, Delay_from_due_date, Num_of_Delayed_Payment, Changed_Credit_Limit, and Num_Credit_Inquiries require positive value but negatives exist. We set these values to NA
In [9]:
columns_to_clear_outliers = ["Age","Num_Bank_Accounts","Num_Credit_Card","Interest_Rate","Num_of_Loan","Num_of_Delayed_Payment","Num_Credit_Inquiries"]

for col in columns_to_clear_outliers:
    q1, q3 = df[col].quantile(0.25), df[col].quantile(0.75)
    lower, upper = q1-1.5*(q3-q1), q3+1.5*(q3-q1)
    df[col][np.logical_or((df[col] > upper), (df[col] < lower))] = pd.NA
    
columns_to_clear_negatives = ["Num_Bank_Accounts", "Num_Credit_Card","Delay_from_due_date", "Num_of_Delayed_Payment", "Changed_Credit_Limit", "Num_Credit_Inquiries"]

for col in columns_to_clear_negatives:
    df.loc[df[df[col]<0].index, col] = pd.NA

3.4 Imputation Strategy for NA Values¶

  • If non-na value exists with same Customer_ID, impute NA with median/model value group by Customer_ID
  • If non-na value doesn't exist with same Customer_ID, impute NA with median/model value of the whole column
  • Following table is NA values ratio in columns before and after the imputation process
In [10]:
columns = (df.isna().mean() * 100).index
before = (df.isna().mean() * 100).values

obj_col = ["Customer_ID","Occupation","Type_of_Loan","Credit_Mix","Payment_of_Min_Amount","Payment_Behaviour"]
num_col = ["Age","Annual_Income","Monthly_Inhand_Salary","Num_Bank_Accounts","Num_Credit_Card","Interest_Rate","Num_of_Loan","Delay_from_due_date","Num_of_Delayed_Payment","Changed_Credit_Limit","Num_Credit_Inquiries","Outstanding_Debt","Credit_Utilization_Ratio","Credit_History_Age","Total_EMI_per_month","Amount_invested_monthly","Monthly_Balance"]

o_m = df[obj_col].groupby("Customer_ID").agg(pd.Series.mode)
n_m = df.groupby(["Customer_ID"]).median()


for col in obj_col[1:]:
    am = pd.Series.mode(df[col])
    for i in df[col][df[col].isna()].index:
        v = o_m.loc[df["Customer_ID"].iloc[i], col]
        if not isinstance(v, np.ndarray):
            df[col].iloc[i] = v
        elif len(v) > 0:
            df[col].iloc[i] = v[0]
        else:
            df[col].iloc[i] = am[0]
            
for col in num_col:
    for i in df[col][df[col].isna()].index:
        v = n_m.loc[df["Customer_ID"].iloc[i], col]
        df[col].iloc[i] = v

after = (df.isna().mean() * 100).values
pd.DataFrame({"Columns": columns, "Before":before, "After":after})

s = set()
for r in df["Type_of_Loan"]:
    s.update(r.split(","))

loan_types = {t: i for i, t in enumerate(s)}

for i in range(len(loan_types)):
    df["Type_of_Loan_" + str(i)] = 0

for i in df.index:
    types = df.iloc[i]["Type_of_Loan"].split(",")
    for t in types:
        df.loc[i, "Type_of_Loan_" + str(loan_types[t])] = 1

df.drop(columns=["Type_of_Loan"], inplace=True)

def showMetrics(clfs, X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test):
    test_results, train_results = [], []
    for clf in clfs:
        y_pred_test = clf.predict(X_test)
        y_pred_train = clf.predict(X_train)
        y_pred_prob_test = clf.predict_proba(X_test)
        y_pred_prob_train = clf.predict_proba(X_train)
        
        accuracy_test = sklearn.metrics.accuracy_score(y_pred_test, y_test)
        precision_macro_test = sklearn.metrics.precision_score(y_pred_test, y_test, average="macro")
        recall_macro_test = sklearn.metrics.recall_score(y_pred_test, y_test, average="macro")
        f1_macro_test = sklearn.metrics.f1_score(y_pred_test, y_test, average="macro")
        auroc_macro_test = sklearn.metrics.roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred_prob_test, multi_class="ovo")
        test_results.append([accuracy_test, precision_macro_test, recall_macro_test, f1_macro_test, auroc_macro_test])

        accuracy_train = sklearn.metrics.accuracy_score(y_pred_train, y_train)
        precision_macro_train = sklearn.metrics.precision_score(y_pred_train, y_train, average="macro")
        recall_macro_train = sklearn.metrics.recall_score(y_pred_train, y_train, average="macro")
        f1_macro_train = sklearn.metrics.f1_score(y_pred_train, y_train, average="macro")
        auroc_macro_train = sklearn.metrics.roc_auc_score(y_train, y_pred_prob_train, multi_class="ovo")
        train_results.append([accuracy_train, precision_macro_train, recall_macro_train, f1_macro_train, auroc_macro_train])
    
    df_test = pd.DataFrame(test_results, index=[clf.__class__.__name__ for clf in clfs], 
                           columns=[["Test", "Test", "Test", "Test", "Test"],
                                    ["Accuracy", "Precision (Macro)", "Recall (Macro)", "F1 Score (Macro)", "AUROC (Macro)"]])
    
    df_train = pd.DataFrame(train_results, index=[clf.__class__.__name__ for clf in clfs], 
                            columns=[["Train", "Train", "Train", "Train", "Train"],
                                     ["Accuracy", "Precision (Macro)", "Recall (Macro)", "F1 Score (Macro)", "AUROC (Macro)"]])
    return pd.concat([df_test, df_train], axis=1)

5.2 First Round Comparison¶

Metrics for multiclass classification problem

  • Accuracy
  • Precision (macro averaging)
  • Recall (macro averaging)
  • F1 Score (macro averaging)
  • AUROC (macro averaging)

As we can expect, ensemble models outperform plain tree classifier and the performance of Random Forest Classifier and Gradient Boosting Classifier are comparable. Due to high dimensionality and nonlinearity of the data, Logistic Regression doesn't perform as well with other models (due to its linear nature).

5.5 Multicollinearity Analysis¶

  • Only Logistic Regression is sensitive to multicollinearity, we use it to test about the effect of correlated features
  • Using VIF as an indicator of the level of multicollinearity
  • We pick different thresholds (e.g. 1.5 or 3) and drop corresponding features
  • The metrics don't improve significantly and some of them even drop a little bit. We conclude that mulcollinearity in the data doesn't affect much to the performance of Logistic Regression

6. Results and Analysis¶

6.1 Classification Metrics¶

  • Since the labels of dataset is not highly imbalanced, accuracy is a good performance indicator
  • In terms of completeness, we also calculate precision, recall, and F1 score for comparison
  • As this is a multiclass classification problem, we need to extend definitions for precision, recall, and F1 score. These metrics use the same way of calculation as their binary counterpart for each label and then average the results (one per label)
  • Finally, AUROC is also included in our metrics for measuring performance of the classifiers under different threshold values when considering different decision criteria
  • ROC curvers are drawn against each labels and macro average for all classifiers.
  • Confusion matrices are also calculated for model comparison
  • Optimal version of classifiers (obtained through hyperparameter tuning) are used

6.2 Summary¶

  • After hyperparameter tuning, the optimal gradient boosting classifier excels in all non-time performance metrics
  • Random forest classifier is the second, but very close to gradient boosting classifier
  • Decision tree classifier is the third, and logistic regression is the last
  • Since the data is not highly imbalanced, model performance is consistent across different metrics
  • If comparison is based on time efficiency, the ranking will be different and the order is: DecisionTreeClassifier (1.52s), LogisticRegression (7.42s), RandomForestClassifier (36.6s), and GradientBoostingClassifier (4min 36s) in terms of trainig time with the complete training data set (without dropping any column)
  • Since RandomForestClassifier has comparable accuracy as GradientBoostingClassifier while possesses good time performance (much better than GradientBoostingClassifer), we recommend using RandomForestCLassifier as the optimal model for this problem

7. Discussion and Conclusion¶

7.1 Learning and Takeaways¶

  • Ensemble model performs better than plain tree model
  • Random forest classifier has accuracy comparable to gradient boosting classifier, depending on the actual problem and characteristics of the data set
  • Decision tree classifier has the fastest training time
  • In this data set, due to high dimensionality and nonlinearity, decision tree classifier performs better than logistic regression
  • Since gradient boosint classifier is based on serial ensembling algorithm, we cannot exploit the benefit of parallel computing and hence it has longest training time
  • Classification metrics defined for binary classification need extension to cope with multiclass classification problem
  • In this study, if a model works better than others, it usually performs better in all metrics. This property might be due to characteristics of the data set
  • Almost half of the features in this data set don't contribute much to the prediction power of the models

7.2 Issue Discussion¶

  • According to the final result, both gradient boosting classifier and randorm forest classifier display certain level of overfitting. As we can see from the performance metrics of training data (most of them are perfect match)
  • Due to the size of the data set, we try to include SVM as one of the model initially but give up later because of long training time
  • Both gradient boosting classifier and random forest classifier require medium size trees (depth = 10-30) in the ensemble instead of small tree (depth = 1-3) to achieve acceptable performance. The reason of this needs further studying

7.3 Possible Future Works¶

  • Other models like KNN, SVM, and deep neural network can be included in this study
  • Finding ways to make trees in the ensemble models smaller
  • A more thorough study of feature selection, for example, if we can find some subsets of the features which produce better performance than the complete data set?
